Yes, you can absolutely deploy this on Azure. Moving from a local setup to Azure changes the "instances" 
from physical hardware to cloud services, but the logic remains the same. 


To keep it as a "self-made" project (avoiding expensive enterprise managed services), you should use 
a container-first approach. 


1. The Deployment Architecture
For a custom budget mapper, you have two main paths on Azure:
Option A: Azure Container Apps (Recommended)
This is best for a "standalone brain" because it handles the scaling and networking for you. You can run 
Ollama and ChromaDB as separate containers within the same "Environment".
Ollama Container: Deploy the official ollama/ollama image. You can even use Serverless GPUs (like the NVIDIA 
T4 or A100) on a consumption basis so you only pay when the "brain" is thinking.
ChromaDB Container: Use the chromadb/chroma image. To make the memory "permanent," you must mount an Azure File 
Share to the container so your user profiles don't disappear when the container restarts.
Option B: Azure Virtual Machine (Maximum Control)
If you want it to feel like your local machine but in the cloud, provision an N-Series VM (which comes with NVIDIA
GPUs). You can SSH into it, install Docker, and run your exact local code. 


2. Implementation Steps on Azure
Storage: Create an Azure Storage Account and a File Share to hold your ChromaDB vector data and Ollama model files.
Container Registry: Push your custom Python "Router" code to an Azure Container Registry (ACR).
Deployment: Use Azure Container Apps to deploy three containers:
Router API: Your Python code (FastAPI/LangGraph).
Ollama: The inference engine.
ChromaDB: The memory store. 


3. Alternative: Hybrid "Brain"
If you find hosting a local LLM on Azure too complex or expensive, you can swap the "brain" for Azure OpenAI 
while keeping the Router and ChromaDB self-made. 


Router: Your custom logic on Azure Container Apps.
Memory: ChromaDB (self-hosted) or Azure Cosmos DB with Vector Search.
Brain: Azure OpenAI API (GPT-4o). 
